    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2372959227" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2372959227" />
    <a title="stormin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3809399-stormin"><img alt="stormin" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2372959227?book_show_action=true">Apr 25, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="stormin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="stormin" href="/user/show/3809399-stormin">stormin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audible Audio " href="/book/show/34522209-genghis-khan-and-the-making-of-the-modern-world">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3809399-stormin?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3809399-stormin?shelf=biography">biography</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2372959227" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10892746004074499341">This was a really incredible book for a lot of reasons, and it&apos;s going to take me a little bit of time to unpack it. <br/><br/>First and foremost, the book successfully overthrew everything I thought I knew about those rampaging Mongol hordes. Now, you think you know how this is going to go: a historical figure we used to think was a hero becomes a villain or (in this case) vice versa. But it&apos;s not that simple. The book in no way glorifies Genghis. But it convinced me that we have his legacy all wrong. <br/><br/>Fi</span>
  <span id="freeText10892746004074499341" style="display:none">This was a really incredible book for a lot of reasons, and it's going to take me a little bit of time to unpack it. <br /><br />First and foremost, the book successfully overthrew everything I thought I knew about those rampaging Mongol hordes. Now, you think you know how this is going to go: a historical figure we used to think was a hero becomes a villain or (in this case) vice versa. But it's not that simple. The book in no way glorifies Genghis. But it convinced me that we have his legacy all wrong. <br /><br />First, he was a relatively enlightened person:<br /><br />&gt;&gt;Although the army of Genghis Khan killed at an unprecedented rate and used death almost as a matter of policy and certainly as a calculated means of creating terror, they deviated from standard practices of the time in an important and surprising way. The Mongols did not torture. mutilate, or maim. War during that time was often a form of combat in terror, and other contemporary rulers used the simple and barbaric tactic of instilling terror and horror into people through public torture or gruesome mutilation. &lt;&lt;<br /><br />Second, the book answered the question of how he won. That's the big one, right? How did this rampaging horde manage to win so many times? I'd heard about their legendary "pretend to run away and then turn on your enemies" routine, but I hadn't had it really explained. In any case, that's not really it. It's only a tiny slice of a much bigger picture. And the bigger picture is this: Genghis Khan was ruthlessly pragmatic:<br /><br />&gt;&gt;Warriors everywhere have been taught to die for their leader, but Genghis Khan never asked his men to die for him. Above all else, he waged war with this strategic purpose in mind: to preserve Mongol life... The Mongols did not find honor in fighting; they found honor in winning.&lt;&lt;<br /><br />This leads to a deeper issue and is a segue into the next thing I want to talk about. It wasn't that Genghis was some kind of military genius savant, so much as it was that a nomadic approach to war was fundamentally different to a settled approach to war. Not to say Genghis wasn't a military genius, but simply to say that his genius had a culturally explicable origin. For example:<br /><br />&gt;&gt;For the soldier farmer, to flee meant to lose; to chase meant to win. The sedentary soldiers sought to drive the attacker away from the place. The nomad sought to kill the enemy, and it mattered not at all whether he killed the enemy while attacking toward him or fleeing from him. For the Mongol, both directions represented fighting; a fleeing conquest was just as good as a stationary one. &lt;&lt;<br /><br />This, along with the prior statement about preserving Mongol life, explain to me how he was able to win so many wars. He didn't play by the same rules as everyone else.<br /><br />So, let's talk just a bit more about that nomad vs. settler thing. This is one of those famous dichotomies that you might hear about a lot in history, literature, and other classes. It goes back at least as far as Cain (settler) and Abel (nomad). <br /><br />These days, it's important to point out, the settlers have won. All modern societies are settled vs. nomadic. The cities won. The nomads lost. All that we have of culture and science comes from city life, and this was true even in Temujin's (Genghis Khan's birth name) day: no matter how many experts the Mongols kidnapped for their empire, that empire was never self-sustaining. They depended on conquest, which is to say: they were essentially parasitic. The cities invented everything. <br /><br />But--lest that sound like a defense of the cities--the cities were rich in their turn because of hierarchical structure. We owe modernity to cities, but it's a tainted birthright. Consider this passage from <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13707734.The_Swerve_How_the_World_Became_Modern" title="The Swerve How the World Became Modern by Stephen Greenblatt" rel="nofollow noopener">The Swerve: How the World Became Modern</a>:<br /><br />&gt;&gt; But cossetted by slaves, in the comfort and security of the elegant villa, the proprietor and his guests had the temporary luxury of regarding these menaces as relatively remote, remote enough at least to allow them to pursue civilized conversations. Staring up idly at the plumes of smoke rising from nearby Vesuvius, they may well have felt some queasiness about the future, but they were an elite, living at the center of the world's greatest power, and one of their most cherished privileges was the cultivation of the life of the mind.&lt;&lt;<br /><br />To put it starkly: slavery paid for "the life of the mind" and not only all of the scientific advances that came from it, but also the foundational values of Western society including, ironically, individual human dignity and rights.<br /><br />It's an uncomfortable story, but Genghis Khan's war with the settled peoples around him reinforces its inescapable verity. Consider:<br /><br />&gt;&gt;By the time Genghis Khan arrived in the Muslim countries of central Asia, he had learned his lesson about the loyalty, dependability, and usefulness of the rich and powerful. In his keen awareness of public attitudes and opinions, he also recognized that the common people cared little about what befell the idle rich. By killing the aristocrats, the Mongols essentially decapitated the social system of their enemies and minimized future resistance. Some of the cities never never recovered enough to rebuild after the losses of aristocrats on the battlefield or from the annihilation of their families.&lt;&lt;<br /><br />This is the counterpoint to Greenblatt's observation (that I paraphrased) that slavery provided for the life of the mind. The other is that settled societies depended--at least historically--on the supremacy of a stable elite. Is this true today? Possibly. <br /><br />The ideology of liberalism seems to lead towards a rejection of that idea and the instinct towards equality has never been stronger: thus all the stuff about the 99% and income inequality. But, as a matter of fact, there's no reason that reality has to conform to ideology. It may very well be the case that, just as slavery fueled the life of the mind and a stable aristocracy kept cities from disintegrating, modern society continues to depend--to a greater or lesser degree--on the twin turbines of exploitation and elitism. I hope it's not true, but the conventional response to the idea--a knee-jerk assumption that it <em>must not</em> be true isn't actually evidence.<br /><br />While we're on depressing themes, here's another one: famous people are all jerks. In the words of Mal, from Firefly, "It's my estimation that every man ever got a statue made of 'em was one kinda sombitch or another."<br /><br />For all that I'm impressed by Genghis Khan's enlightened qualities--such as banning torture and instituting freedom of religion--this is the same guy that murdered his older brother in cold blood when he was still a kid. He and his younger brother snuck up on their older brother--who was unarmed--and approached to within killing range armed with bow and arrow. The older brother was totally defenseless, and they shot him. From that point on through the rest of his career, one of the reasons his reign was as relatively bloodless as it was must be his willingness to be brutally deadly when he wanted to be. Everything from breaking the back of a man who had humiliated a friend--even after that man surrendered and apologized--to wiping out entire cities if they refused to surrender, the historical record seems to indicate that although Genghis Khan wasn't particularly bloodthirsty he was also completely and totally consienceless when it came to killing. Which, based on arguments like those in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/78127.On_Killing_The_Psychological_Cost_of_Learning_to_Kill_in_War_and_Society" title="On Killing The Psychological Cost of Learning to Kill in War and Society by Dave Grossman" rel="nofollow noopener">On Killing: The Psychological Cost of Learning to Kill in War and Society</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/72536.The_Sociopath_Next_Door" title="The Sociopath Next Door by Martha Stout" rel="nofollow noopener">The Sociopath Next Door</a> definitely seems sociopathic. <br /><br />Compared to the other figures of the time, Genghis was a saint. But that happy result seems to be entirely the result of his total lack of inhibition to murder.<br /><br />So, let's come to the main thesis of the book. Instead of obliterating civilization wherever he encountered it, is it possible that Genghis Khan actually helped <em>create</em> the modern world? This unlikely thesis is amply supported by the evidence, and it boils down to two key points.<br /><br />First, by conquering such a huge swath of the planet and then shuffling experts all around the empire, Genghis Khan facilitated a massive transfer of knowledge on a global scale. Moreover, he was a genuine innovator, including such concepts as paper money (seriously! modern finance like whoa), rule of law, weight and measurement standardization, and even a ridiculously efficient postal organization.<br /><br />Second, by leaving Europe unconquered, Genghis Khan gave them all the benefits of this information-sharing (because the Europeans were close enough to benefit from all the information that the Mongol Empire had spread within itself) without the costs of actually getting conquered and having their cities razed and elites massacred.<br /><br />So far so theoretical, but one of the most persuasive passages for me was the examination of how much Mongol culture suffused Renaissance painting in, for example, the style and dress of the people depicted along with the popularity of putting horses in paintings. On the other extreme, it's hard to dismiss the fact that Beijing is still the capital of China, when it was a city created entirely by the Mongols (Genghis's grandson) right down to the original, Mongol Forbidden City. The Mongol Forbidden City--unlike the one that was built later--was a way for the Mongol rulers of China to preserve a tiny slice of their nomadic culture within the walls of their capital city and far from the prying eyes of their Chinese subjects (who would have viewed Mongol traditions with disgust and contempt if they'd been allowed to see them).<br /><br />The impact of the Mongols was so great on Europe that it was specifically the Mongolian Empire that Christopher Columbus set out to find. They didn't know that the empire had fallen by then, and assumed that it was just a matter of Muslim and other kingdoms gobbling up some of the land territory between Europe and Asia. So when Columbus got to the Caribbean and found the natives, he assumed that Mongolia was just a bit farther north, which is why he called the Native Americans "Indians".<br /><br />It's a pretty complete upheaval of everything I was ever taught about the Mongols, but I'm convinced.<br /><br />Last thing: the story of how this information about Genghis Khan was uncovered is a thrilling tale in its own right. After horrific repression under the hands of the Communists--who literally banned Mongolians from setting foot on the sacred ground of Genghis Khan's nativity--it's only been in the last couple of decades that The Secret Book of the Mongols (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Secret_History_of_the_Mongols" rel="nofollow noopener">a real thing</a>) and access to those once-banned lands inside Mongolia has allowed researchers like Weatherford (and, much more than that, Mongolian researchers) to recover Genghis Khan's true legacy.<br /><br />Like the book says: he conquered more territory in 25 years than the Romans did in 400. And he really did contribute to the "Making of the Modern World".</span>
  <a data-text-id="10892746004074499341" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

